segments.text: It is August 1st.
This is the third interview with General Hanover.
This is the last or the third and probably last interview with General Hanover.
Today is August 1st, 1980.
Today let's talk about
the military and leadership and the changes that have taken place at Texas A&M.
All right.
How does one get ahead in the military?
Is it different from professional life in business or in academics?
Are there similarities?
Terry, I really don't think there are any differences.
Basically, leadership is leadership wherever you are, in my opinion.

And I think they all come about by a person striving to excel and making those that you're leading feel like they can be led properly and setting an example of the way you expect people to work or to follow, whichever it may be, whether it's military, civilian, or whatever.
OK. Now, when you think back on your military career and advancement
Did you leave advancement to all, let's say, fate, the decisions of others, or did you think that your advancement was because of your actions?
Well, it's bound to be a little of both.
I think the basic part of it is a person himself as to how he progresses, how his...
feelings toward whether he wants to advance, there are some people who do not want to advance.
There are some people who do not want to be leaders.
They want to be led.
And so it's a great percent of what a person puts himself in as to his own feelings, his own actions, but there is always that part of it that
the positions become available because many times two people could be almost exact leader, have leadership qualities, and one may have opportunities where the other does never get them.
So the majority of it, I would say, is a person himself, his actions, his reactions, but there must be openings for climbing up the ladder.
Yeah, yeah.
Very few men obtain the success that you've had.
Very few become generals or become directors in charge of a highway district.
Do you feel that during your career you would consider yourself ambitious?
Yes, I was ambitious.
I wanted to, I wanted to move up.
I wanted to
Get in a position of responsibility.
I like responsibility.
I like to lead.
Of course, I think a good leader at some point likes to be led.
You must be led early in the game.
Of course, a person never gets to the place where he's not led by someone.
Unless it's like Truman said, the buck stops here.
There's one or two places in the world that the buck stops.
But even in my two positions of leadership, there were those above me who, you must say, were leading me or giving me the opportunity to follow.
And even though the president, of course, there, at least in a democracy, seemed to be led quite a bit by popular opinion.
Theoretically.
Theoretically.
I think that was a clever saying.
And to a degree, it's correct.
Now, of course, retirement is a substantial change in an individual's life.
Why did you retire from the military?
Well, I had forced military retirement because under the rules and regulations, certain ranks have certain areas you can move up through, but there are points to where
At a certain time, if you have not moved further or if you do not move out of a position, then you will have mandatory retirement.
Now, there are not too many brigadier generals.
There are less major generals.
So there are some people who got to be major generals who were in a little more favorable position than I. I never had that opportunity.
I think I would have liked to have had it if I had that opportunity, but I have no regrets as to the position that I got to.

I don't feel like that, you know, the gate was shut to me and that I have a resentment that I didn't get to be a major general because that would have taken more time on my part, more effort, and I thought I was very successful as I was and I felt a great sense of accomplishment.
So it was really mandatory as far as the
Was there a rule, were you alluding to the day before yesterday, a rule that after you were in a grade for five years, then it was mandatory retirement?
In the grade of Brigadier General, at the time that I reached that position, you could either stay five years in grade
are 30 years of service, whichever came later.
And the five years in grade came later for me because I had 31 and a half years of total service.
So there is a stopping point.
You're not allowed to just stay and stay when you reach either so much in grade or so many years in service.
Now, do you remember your thoughts on the day that you retired?
Can you tell me about that?
Very well.
I had no animosity at all to the service for putting me out.
I was highly pleased that I had accomplished the thing that I had.
I had been working very hard over the last two to three years that I was in command.
I spent a great deal of weekends, a great deal of nights,
And this had deprived me of a lot of time with my family.
It was part of the job.
And taking the job, I did that.
But I think I felt that I had reached a point that I could take a deep breath and say, you know, I'm going to have some time of my own.
So I really felt like I had sort of reached

pinnacle that I was looking for I had gotten to the top of the mountain I could see on the other side and I was ready to go back down if that makes any sense and it's a great deal of sense and another thing that gave me satisfaction I knew who was going to take my place or at least I was pretty certain and I felt like that

The command structure was in good hands, and it would, as I told someone, each time you get a new leader, you get new ideas, you get new motives, you get new thoughts, and I can't help but to believe that a change of command many times enhances an organization.
I didn't feel like I had all the answers, in other words.
A new man had new answers,
A lot of times a new room is sweet to clean, you know.
Plus you had your civilian crew to look forward to.
That's correct.
And how many more years did you have to look forward in the highway department?
Well, actually, I had, at that time, I had about, let's see, well, I must have had about four or five more
prior to mandatory retirement.
But I was not anticipating going to mandatory retirement.
At that time, you had to retire at the highway department at 65.
And I guess in 71, I was, well, I guess I was 57.
So I'd have had eight years that I could have worked.
But I didn't plan to work all that length of time.
How long did you want to work?
I had the plan to work till about 60, which would have been five years ahead of mandatory.
And the reason for that was, well, really two things.
One, I wanted to retire early as soon as I felt like I financially could do so.
And as you know, you draw a reservist or a reserve army people draw their retirement at 60.
And I had sort of planned that that would be a point that I could afford to retire.
That plus my highway pay would enable me to retire and live comfortably.
And so you did retire at age 60?
Well, just prior to.
In fact, I was going to retire at 60, but the retirement of the highway department comes under the state legislature, and they made a few last-minute changes which made it
economically feasible or economically advantageous to me to retire in August prior to the following February, which I planned to retire.
So I retired, well, August ahead of my 60th birthday in February.
Are you happy that you retired?
Absolutely.
I have never regretted retirement, not one minute.
In fact, my first day of retirement was three years ago today.
I retired on July 31st.
So three years ago today, I was a retired person from the military and the highway department.
And it was a great day, and I've had three years of great time since.
Now, that would not be possible for a person like me unless you have outside injuries.
Absolutely.
And I had many outside interests and I was looking forward to getting into those.
I had not had time to do that during the years that I was active in the Reserve and Highway Department and I have just really had a ball.
Been delightful.
Let's talk about leadership.
You started to define leadership just a few minutes ago.
Could you define it for me?

Well, other than those things that I said, the ability to lead, the ability to understand being led, the ability to decide courses of action that are both advantageous for you and your organization and those that are being led, your ability to see, I think, an end

through the possible problems that may arise and I think also the ability to to analyze problems as they do crop up and to be able to accomplish a mission set out with with the and I always think with the good feeling of those that are being led there are leaders
in my opinion, who lead by sheer force and by sheer determination, regardless of how it affects those who are led.
And there are successful people at that.
And I really think one of my best definitions of one of those was Patton.
Patton, without question, was a leader.
an absolute leader, but he led behind the feeling of those that were being led.
And that is not my philosophy.
And I don't mean by that that you can lead and keep your lead happy all the time.
But I think that the feelings, I think the concern and welfare of those that are being led is part of the marks of a leader.
You can't argue with success, but I am a different type leader than Patton was.
Of course, he was in a much, much more important position than I, but my philosophies are different than his.

Now, sometimes when you talk about, or I've heard in the past when people talk about, they talk about military leaders, and then they talk about political leaders, and they talk about other types of civilian leaders.

Do you think there is a difference between the military type leader, maybe you were alluding to it a minute ago, and when you talked about Patton, Patton's sort of a kick-em-in-the-you-know-where, an over-the-hill-boys type leader, and sometimes civilians get the idea that that's what military leadership is.
What do you think about that?
No, I think a lot of qualities of leadership depend on the individual.
I think my qualities of leadership and yours could be entirely different, and they could both be highly successful.
And here again, comparing, I could not attempt to lead like Patton did, and he probably couldn't have been successful as I led.
He's just got a different philosophy.
But each end, of course, a lot of qualities of leadership everybody's got.
I think there's a lot of it that is common to everybody.
But the specifics of leadership depend a great deal on the individual and his ability to interpret and to impart to the subordinates and react to the
superiors are entirely different.
What about personal values in leadership?
I mean, do you think that an individual has to have certain values?
I sure do.
Like, for example?
Well, I think you've got to be honest.
I think you've got to be straightforward.
I think you've got to be open.
I think you've got to have an appreciation of

those that are being led there are a lot of values and I guess here again those could differ with the leader but in my opinion those four or five are very important and I'm sure there are a great many others do you feel that you have those values well I was aware of them all the time and and attempted that it was my intent to have those things and I worked at it I
If I didn't fulfill those, it was accidentally not intentional because I think they're very important.
I think one that I have always felt like was real important was recognition of jobs well done.
After it is done, I think you've got to begin with
You've got to begin by telling people what you expect, being explicit and having two-way communication.
But then after the job is done, whether it's done right or wrong, some type of recognition.
Hopefully, a pat on the back.
I think anybody who looks to somebody for leadership wants to know if they don't do it right.
And I think that's important.
I think there's a proper way to tell them it's right or it's wrong.
Those are my thinking about that sort of thing.
This is sort of a similar question.
But nevertheless, I think it's important.
You said that you had intent to become a good leader.
Let's say you were talking to a group of corpsmen today over at A&M, and the topic was,
how to become a leader.
Are these some of the things that you'd say, and are there others?
Yes.
I think for a man to be a leader, he has to want to be a leader.
People that, and I say people, because we're mainly talking about leading people, I think, but people that are led

want to know that their leader does want to be a leader it's i i have been in situations where i was being led by people who either didn't have an interest in what they were doing or they really didn't care about being leaders and it's very evident to me yeah and i want to be led by someone who has my interest who has his interest who's got a goal
and who wants to be a leader, I look to people that are not interested in what they're doing and are not really concerned about success.
And really, it's not going to succeed a great much of the time.
And I think a good leader has to be an optimist.
That's another one.
I think a good leader has got to be an optimist.
Because I'd rather be an optimist and be wrong than a pessimist and be right.
So I think optimism plays a great part.
That's another value, probably.
That's right.
What about tolerance?
You've got to be tolerant.
You've got to be tolerant.
Because everybody's not going to do exactly like you want them to do.
And if you can show people here again, I'm talking
I'm speaking of my own thoughts.
My own, yeah.
Patton certainly probably wasn't tolerant.
That's right.
But it worked for him in some manner.
It almost caused his downfall in others.
But if you're tolerant with people, then they're not going to be afraid to act.
If a person is afraid to make a mistake,
then he's not going to do much because everybody feels that he has the possibility of making a mistake.
And if he makes a mistake and he knows that he's going to just catch hell from every side, then he's reluctant to do a whole lot.
And of course, those that worked for Patton for years, I guess,
came to recognize that as part of working for him.
But I'd say he did not have tolerance, and tolerance, in my opinion, is a quality of leadership.
Nor did he have flexibility.
That's right.
And you think that in your idea of leadership, is flexibility important?
It plays a part.
It sure does.
You're a rigid person, a person who says, my idea is the only one.
You're
you're just heading for some disaster, in my opinion.
Another quality of leadership, I think, and I think I had this, or at least I attempted to, and that is to be receptive to the idea of others.
There's no one person who's got all the answers.
And I continually sought
and was demanding that other people give me their ideas for whatever the problem was, whatever the decision I was making, I used my staff to a great degree, I think.
I certainly intended to, and I believe I was successful in that.
There are suggestions?
Yes, yes.
Input from...
staff, assistants, subordinates.
What about mustard men?

I've gotten some some from them too you know that's uh gosh they've they've got more ideas than you ever saw some of them are far-fetched but pitch it out the window but evaluate it right if you don't need it.
A man to me was not too low on the pole to have a good idea.
I've had some
Tremendous suggestions from, I'll use the word, raw recruits, you know, people who just moved in with the picture.
I really never ridiculed any suggestions.
I like to take them and spin them around and bring it out and see if it's any good.
Another thing I think a leader has got to have and that is the ability to finally make up his mind and act and not to continually wonder if you made a good decision.
A decision has to be made and acted upon and then that is down the river.
Go to the next problem because there's not anything you can do about that one
And here again, I've seen people who could make a decision, but then they'd just continue to worry about whether it was a good decision.
And I think that's time and effort lost.
You just mentioned your staff.
Can you tell me about the quality of the staff that you were commanding?
Well, I selected most of them.
I ought to have thought they were pretty good.
But you had a large pool of quality then to select from.
That's right.
I don't mean they all were top notch.
Here again, everybody has their own limitations.
But I have had both civilian and military some very fine assistance.
And I've always
be the first to say that those who were helping me had a great deal to do with the success that I had.
I don't by any means feel that I attained the rank in the military or the position in the highway department by myself.
I had a lot of help, and there were probably many others who were just as qualified as I, and I got some breaks.
Maybe they didn't.
But it wasn't done by myself, my whole life.
As we've already established, your ideas of leadership are much different than General Patton's.
I know that this is an impossible question to answer, really, but I'd just like your thoughts on this.
Do you think that in the military, more people have the idea of leadership that you have or General Patton?
Well, that is a hard question.
I don't know of very many leaders who reached the level, say, that Patton did that had the leadership qualities that he had.
I think he was sort of one out of many.
I don't believe
across the board that very many people could be as successful as Patton was with his qualities of leadership.
I believe there have been more successful leaders with more of my style or the style that I like to feel I fall in than his style.
I think he's
I think he's on the extreme far side of the middle of the road type leaders, in my opinion.
So if I had to make a guess, I'd say Moore followed my style and followed his style.
Would you say that your style runs closer to someone, let's say, like General Eisenhower?
Well, I don't know that I can put myself in his style, but he
He was more of a soldier's leader than was Patton.
And I liked to feel like I was a soldier's leader or a civilian leader, whatever.
So my style was, I'd say, a whole lot more like him than it was like Patton.
Another question.
You were a leader in war?
on a smaller scale during the Second World War, and you're also a leader on a larger scale during peacetime.
Is it more difficult to be a leader during war or during peace in the military?
Well, more difficult, I'm not sure I know what you mean.
There are more difficulties arising in war, of course, but I really don't think that there's any difference
and leadership no matter the situation.

Now, there are hardships and there are turmoils and there are disasters that happen during wartime or emergency times that may take more far-reaching decisions or decisions that affect a lot more people.
But I really don't believe that there's really any difference in good leadership, whatever the situation.
What about the idea of cause?
The men having a cause.
World War II was a time when the country was united, perhaps like no time before in American history.
We have a cause.
Do you think that has any impact on helping a leader become a great leader, or helping an individual become a leader?
Oh, it's bound to.
If soldiers are motivated by common cause, so to speak, there's no question that it makes leadership easier.
But still, the basics of leadership are there regardless.
If people are unmotivated or if the morale is low from other standpoints, then it just adds some more responsibilities to leadership that I think a good leader has.
And it just tries them out a little bit harder.
But it's a good point.
They were motivated.
regardless of who the leader was.
But really, war or otherwise, I don't really look at it as any more difficult one way or the other.
I think responsibilities and problems of leadership are there, whatever the situation.

Of course, leadership is an important question politically today, because it seems like ever since 1968, when President Johnson said he was no longer going to run for re-election, and then we had Watergate, it seems like we've had a leadership crisis, at least the journalists seem to say that we've had this leadership crisis in America.
How could we resolve this?
